questionTemplates.text:
W: Shall we have an English test this afternoon?
M: It is postponed because the teacher has attend a meeting.
{a}

F: We are going to visit the flower exhibition tomorrow.
M: Are you? May I join you?
{a}

W: You've got your apartment furnished, haven't you?
M: Yes, I bought some furniture in the used furniture market. It was a real bargain.
{a}

M: Susan, I heard you are going to France. How long will you be staying there?
W: A whole year. My aunt lives there. I'm going to do a one-month course at a language school and spend the rest of the time traveling.
{a}

M: The skirt is beautiful. I want to buy it for Jane.
W: OK. But you'd better send another thing to Jane's brother, or he will angry.
{a}

W: The children want to stay longer to see the panda.
M: OK. Let them have a good time here.
{a}

W: I'm taking Prof. Barn's course next semester. Anything I need to know about it?
M: If I were you, I'd take careful notes. Her exams are based on her lectures.
{a}

M: Mom, I don't want to eat vegetables. Can I have dessert now? I love chocolate cake!
W: You can have some fruit for dessert. If you eat an apple, I might let you have a small piece of chocolate cake.
{a}

F: I should have told Alice the news.
M: It's not your fault. If I were you, I wouldn't tell her either.
{a}

W: Do you want your son to be a dancer?
M: Not really. I expect him to manage my store when I retire.
{a}

M: Would you hurry up? The film starts at 8:00.
W: So we still have one hour to get there.
{a}

M: Shall we go to the airport to meet Dr. Smith this afternoon?
W: Oh, I forgot to tell you. He has put off his trip.
{a}

W: Excuse me. Can you tell me the way to Central Square?
M: Take the second turn on the right and there you are.
{a}

W: May I have this prescription filled here? I have a terrible stomachache.
M: Yes, but you'll have a 15-minute wait.
{a}

W: How can I get to the airport?
M: You can go there by underground, by bus or by taxi. The underground is the quickest. But the bus is the cheapest.
{a}

W: You've sold your car. You don't need one?
M: Not really. I've never liked driving anyway. Now we've moved to a place near the subway entrance. We can get about quite conveniently.
{a}

W: Are you ready to order now, Sir?
M: Yes. I'll have tomato soup, roast beef, mashed potatoes, and peas.
{a}

M: How about this red dress, Ann? It's very fashionable.
W: I don't know. I'm not crazy about red. I think it's a hit too bright for me.
{a}

M: Did you have a good time at the party?
F: Our car broke down and we didn't get there.
{a}

M: Hi, Grace. Tell me something about your hometown.
W: It's so beautiful and peaceful. But it's really far away from everything.
{a}

M: Dear, the film Harry Porter will be shown this evening in the cinema.
W: Well, to be honest I'd rather stay at home.
{a}

W: Have you found your youngest brother, Tom?
M: Yes. He was picked up by a policeman.
{a}

W: Did you miss the beginning of the concert yesterday?
M: The concert began as soon as I arrived at the hall.
{a}

F: Do you have to change planes in Tokyo, Jim?
M: Certainly. We arrive there at ten and leave at twelve.
{a}
